Battle Maison Pokémon

The following Pokémon are used in the Battle Maison. Every individual species used by these facilities can have between two and four movesets associated with them. There are roughly four groups of 'power levels' of species that can be encountered:

  1. Low Tier: Consists largely of first-stage Pokémon and some weak evolved Pokémon. Species in this tier have two sets associated with them.
  2. Mid Tier: Consists largely of middle-stage Pokémon and some weak fully evolved Pokémon. Species in this tier have two sets associated with them.
  3. High Tier: Consists largely of fully-evolved Pokémon. Species in this tier have four sets associated with them.
  4. Legendary Tier: Consists of all Legendaries that are legal in the Battle Maison. Species in this tier have four sets associated with them.

The common way of referring to a Pokémon with multiple sets is to identify the set with a number, e.g. "Set2 Rayquaza", "Rayquaza1", or "Rayquaza-3". For my tables, I will be using the "Rayquaza-1" method of referring to sets.

Trainer Set Mechanics

Any enemy Trainer the player faces, apart from the Battle Chatelaine, will be pulled from a pre-existing list of 300 Trainers. Each Trainer has a roster of Pokémon and an IV value associated with them, and the game will choose three random Pokémon from their roster to make the player battle. The chosen Pokémon will never be the same species or have the same held item as each other. The Trainers page gives more detail and shows each Trainer's roster.

Trainers 1-110 can only appear in the Normal Course, and Trainers 111-300 can only appear in the Super Course.

The first 220 Trainers on the list are split into eight groups, where each group can only use one set of Pokémon from a specific tier. Trainers 221-300 have some Trainers that can use Pokémon from multiple sets, as well as Legendaries.

The number of battles the player has participated in will determine which Trainers can be selected as enemies, and therefore, which sets of Pokémon the player might face. The progression proceeds as follows:

Normal Course

  • Battles 1-5: Set-1 Low Tier, 3IV
  • Battles 6-10: Set-1 Low Tier, 3IV or Set-2 Low Tier, 7IV
  • Battles 11-15: Set-2 Low Tier, 7IV or Set-1 Mid Tier, 11IV
  • Battles 16-19: Set-1 Mid Tier, 11IV or Set-2 Mid Tier, 15IV
  • Battle 20: Battle Chatelaine, 15IV

Super Course

  • Battles 1-10: Set-1 High Tier, 19IV
  • Battles 11-20: Set-1 High Tier, 19IV or Set-2 High Tier, 23IV
  • Battles 21-30: Set-2 High Tier, 23IV or Set-3 High Tier, 27IV
  • Battles 31-40: Set-3 High Tier, 27IV or Set-4 High Tier, 31IV
  • Battles 41-49: Any High or Legendary Tier, 31IV
  • Battle 50: Battle Chatelaine, 31IV
  • Battles 51+: Any High or Legendary Tier, 31IV

Some additional resources:

  • This page contains a damage calculator with all the movesets of High- and Legendary-Tier Battle Maison Pokémon pre-loaded, using the numbers for each set. Remember that you will need to update the IVs yourself in accordance with the Trainer faced.
  • This post contains some Speed values associated with enemy Pokémon with 31 IVs. This can be useful for determining what kinds of Speed benchmarks your Pokémon will need to hit to accomplish their goals.
  • The spreadsheet tool linked in this post all of the High and Legendary Tier Pokémon, a list of Pokémon that can be used by Trainers 111-300, and a lookup function that allows you to identify what movesets a given Trainer might have.
  • This tool also allows you to enter Trainer and Pokémon information to get movesets.
